{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UKrD9XUEqoFBdby4BtmiB5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n1. **Products marked as out-of-stock are excluded from recommendation results regardless of relevance score.**\n   - MOCK-MISS: This is about filtering logic — does a filter function correctly exclude out-of-stock items? This is a single function's logic that checks availability status. It doesn't require multiple modules interacting.\n   - REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed.\n   - MOCK-HIDE: Could mock the catalog; the filter logic itself is testable in isolation.\n   - LLM-DEP: No LLM involved.\n   - MULTI-STEP: No.\n   - Minimum level: **Unit** — filter function logic, no I/O needed.\n\n2. **User preference filter correctly excludes blocked categories.**\n   - MOCK-MISS: Similar to #1 — this is filter logic based on user settings. One function or module boundary.\n   - REAL-INFRA: No.\n   - MOCK-HIDE: The filter logic is self-contained.\n   - LLM-DEP: No.\n   - Minimum level: **Unit** — preference filtering logic.\n\n3. **Recommendation algorithm** — now I need to evaluate whether this involves multiple steps or cross-module interactions that would push it beyond unit testing.\n\nThe ranking algorithm's core logic is whether it correctly weights browsing signals, which I can test with synthetic data showing known browsing patterns. The key question is whether this uses an ML model or a traditional weighted scoring approach — the issue description suggests a traditional algorithm combining purchase history, browsing patterns, and similar-user behavior, which would keep it at unit or integration level rather than agentic. The test would verify that the algorithm prioritizes products matching recent browsing correctly.\n\nSince ranking requires multiple data sources (browsing signals, product data, user history) to be combined together, I'm settling on **Integration** as the minimum test level — the algorithm itself is deterministic and testable, but it depends on multiple components feeding it the right signals.\n\nNow moving to pagination — I need to check whether it returns the correct page with stable ordering.  The key question is whether the underlying ranking produces deterministic output or if there's randomness involved. If ranking is non-deterministic, then pagination will fail even with correct logic. This still points to **Integration** since I need the full ranking pipeline wired up to verify pagination works correctly.\n\nFor the serendipity requirement, I'm weighing whether this is a standalone algorithm concern or a post-processing step. If it's baked into the ranking logic itself, that's **Integration**. But if it's applied afterward as a filter or reordering rule, it could drop to **Unit** level.\n\nFor the cold-start case, I'm realizing this could actually be **Unit** if the ranking function is designed to handle empty history as a valid input and explicitly switches to popularity scoring. The integration concern only matters if the history lookup and fallback logic are tightly coupled.\n\nFor click tracking, the position calculation is the tricky part—it depends on knowing where the product sits in the recommendation list, which crosses module boundaries, so this needs **Integration** testing to verify the event handler correctly extracts and passes both the product ID and its position to the tracking store.\n\nPerformance under 100K products requires **System**-level testing with real data volume and infrastructure, since mocking the catalog would mask any actual performance bottlenecks.\n\nFor deprioritizing purchased products, I need to verify the full chain: the purchase event gets recorded, the algorithm reads that history, and the ranking logic actually filters it out.  This is **Integration**-level since the failure happens at the boundary between purchase tracking and the recommendation algorithm.\n\nFor determinism, I'm considering whether the ranking function itself is deterministic (Unit-level) or if the entire pipeline needs to be tested end-to-end (Integration-level).  If components are individually deterministic but something like dictionary ordering or thread scheduling introduces non-determinism in the final result, I need Integration testing to catch that. So this is also **Integration**.\n\nNow I'm finalizing my test level assessments, starting with out-of-stock exclusion. I'm verifying each test level matches what's actually needed — the unit tests for stock filtering and preference blocking are straightforward, but everything from ranking onward requires integration or system-level setup because they depend on multiple components working together. Now I'm calculating the probability distribution for each scenario to understand confidence levels. Looking at how different test categories weight across more scenarios—cold-start behavior heavily favors integration testing, click tracking similarly relies on integration, while response time is almost entirely a system-level concern, and purchase deprioritization might benefit from agentic approaches like the browsing pattern ranking does.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9588,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9588},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"473af50b-708d-444f-8e2c-7240b1c33f3f","uuid":"3c8f5750-9a1b-4a18-a0db-c7121736939d"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UKrD9XUEqoFBdby4BtmiB5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01H8ngByJo2VDhqwpuXTvxMA","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Out-of-stock products are excluded from recommendations regardless of relevance score.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is in a single filter predicate — does the availability flag gate the product list correctly? This is one function's logic; no module handoff is needed to expose the bug. The failure appears even if the scoring/ranking pipeline is mocked. REAL-INFRA: None. LLM-DEP: No. The filter either checks the flag or it doesn't.","test_description":"Construct a product list with mixed in-stock/out-of-stock items spanning a range of relevance scores (including the highest score assigned to an out-of-stock item). Call the availability filter function directly. Assert that the returned list contains zero out-of-stock products and that all in-stock products are present, regardless of score.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"User preference filter excludes product categories the user has explicitly blocked.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is in the preference-filter predicate: given a user's blocked-category list and a product catalog, does the function remove all products in blocked categories? This is self-contained logic with no cross-module handoff needed to expose the failure. REAL-INFRA: None. LLM-DEP: No.","test_description":"Create a synthetic user preferences object with two blocked categories and a product list containing products in blocked, unblocked, and mixed-category memberships. Invoke the preference filter function directly. Assert that no returned product belongs to a blocked category and that products in unblocked categories are all retained.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.16,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The ranking algorithm scores products matching recent browsing patterns higher than products with no browsing signal.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Verifying that browsing signal actually elevates rank requires the browsing-history loader and the ranking scorer to be wired together; the failure appears at the handoff where browsing data is read and applied to scores. A unit test mocking the history would trivially pass. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the history store hides whether the algorithm actually reads and applies the signal correctly. LLM-DEP: A traditional weighted scorer is deterministic, but if the engine uses an ML ranker the quality claim becomes Agentic — probability reflected below.","test_description":"Seed a local in-memory browsing-history store with events for product A (high signal) and no events for product B (same base attributes). Run the full recommendation ranking pipeline against both products. Assert that product A receives a higher rank than product B and that the rank difference is attributable to the browsing-signal weight.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Pagination returns the correct page slice with stable ordering across repeated requests.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Stability failures arise at the boundary between the ranking module (which must produce a deterministically ordered list) and the pagination module (which slices it). A unit test of pagination alone would trivially pass with a fixed input list; the real risk is that the ranked list order varies between calls, making page 2 inconsistent. REAL-INFRA: None needed; a local in-memory data store suffices. LLM-DEP: No.","test_description":"Populate a local product store with 50 products and a fixed user state. Request page 2 (e.g., items 11–20) twice in sequence with no data changes. Assert that both responses return the same ordered product IDs and that the set is exactly the expected slice of the full ranked list (no overlap with page 1, no duplicates).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"At least one recommendation comes from a category the user has not browsed (serendipity requirement).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Serendipity enforcement requires the browsing-history module and the diversity/serendipity post-processor to be wired together; the failure only appears when the system actually reads the user's browsed categories and then checks that the final list contains at least one outside them. Mocking history would hide whether category diversity is computed from real signal. LLM-DEP: A rule-based serendipity filter is deterministic; if an ML ranker controls category selection, the quality guarantee becomes Agentic.","test_description":"Create a user with browsing history covering exactly two categories. Populate a catalog with products in those two categories and products in two additional categories. Run the full recommendation pipeline. Assert that the returned list contains at least one product whose category does not appear in the user's browsing history.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A new user with no purchase or browsing history receives popularity-based recommendations, not an empty result.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The cold-start failure is a routing bug at the boundary between the history-fetching module (returning empty/null) and the ranking algorithm (which must branch to a popularity fallback instead of returning empty). A unit test that directly calls the ranker with an empty-history argument bypasses the real failure point — whether the pipeline detects the cold-start condition and invokes the fallback at all. REAL-INFRA: None. LLM-DEP: No.","test_description":"Register a user with no purchase or browsing history in the local history store. Also seed a popularity index with known top-N products. Run the full recommendation pipeline for this user. Assert that (a) the result is non-empty, (b) the returned products match the global popularity rankings, and (c) no personalized signal was applied.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"Click tracking records the correct product ID, position in the recommendation list, and timestamp.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: 'Position in the list' is derived from the recommendation list, not from the click event alone — the tracking handler must receive or compute position relative to the rendered result set. The failure appears at the boundary where the recommendation list is passed to (or accessible by) the tracking module. A unit test of the tracking function with a hard-coded position would not catch a bug where position is mis-calculated from the list. REAL-INFRA: Local in-memory or filesystem event store suffices. LLM-DEP: No.","test_description":"Generate a recommendation list of 10 products using the local pipeline with a seeded data store. Simulate a click on the product at position 4 (0-indexed). Call the click-tracking module with the recommendation context. Read back the tracking record and assert that product_id, position (4), and timestamp (within a small tolerance) are all recorded correctly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"Recommendation response time stays under 200ms for a catalog of 100,000 products.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Performance depends on real computation and I/O over real data volume; any mock of the catalog trivially eliminates the latency. REAL-INFRA: Requires a real data store populated with 100K products, real network or subprocess calls, and real CPU/memory allocation. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the catalog would make this test meaningless — it would always pass. LLM-DEP: No. The 200ms SLA is only observable under realistic infrastructure.","test_description":"Seed a real (or containerized) product database with 100,000 product records reflecting realistic field cardinality. Issue a recommendation request for a user with a representative history profile. Measure wall-clock latency from request dispatch to response received (including all filtering, ranking, and pagination). Assert the measured latency is below 200ms across at least 10 consecutive runs (to rule out cold-start outliers).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":9,"description":"A product purchased by the user is deprioritized in subsequent recommendation requests.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is at the boundary between the purchase-event recorder and the ranking algorithm: the purchase must be persisted, then read back and applied as a deprioritization signal in the next ranking call. A unit test of the ranker with a hard-coded purchase list bypasses the real failure point — whether the pipeline actually reads and applies the purchase record on a subsequent call. REAL-INFRA: Local in-memory store suffices. LLM-DEP: Deprioritization may be rule-based (deterministic) or ML-influenced; probability reflected below.","test_description":"Generate an initial recommendation list for a user and note the rank of product X. Record a purchase event for product X in the local purchase store. Generate a second recommendation list for the same user with unchanged catalog data. Assert that product X's rank is lower in the second list than in the first (or that it is absent if fully suppressed), and that no other product's relative order has changed due to the purchase signal.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":10,"description":"Recommendations are deterministic — two requests with identical user state return the same ranked list.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Non-determinism in the full pipeline is more likely to originate from hash-map ordering, floating-point tiebreaking, or thread scheduling across modules than within a single function. A unit test of the ranker in isolation with a fixed input will always be deterministic; the failure only surfaces when the full pipeline (history fetch → scoring → sort → paginate) is exercised end-to-end. REAL-INFRA: No external infrastructure needed. LLM-DEP: If the ranker uses an LLM/ML model, determinism cannot be guaranteed — but the behavior explicitly requires it, making Agentic the level if ML is involved.","test_description":"Fix a user state (browsing history, preferences, purchase history) in the local in-memory stores. Call the full recommendation pipeline twice in sequence with no intervening mutations. Assert that both responses return identical product ID sequences in identical order and that all metadata (scores, page info) matches exactly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.12,"Workflow":0.03}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9588,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9588},"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"473af50b-708d-444f-8e2c-7240b1c33f3f","uuid":"f2634ac3-f015-44ca-994f-67e86d5972ba"}
